Proposed (19.5s): Use this skill whenever the user is implementing, debugging, or reviewing the Agent Execution Protocol (AEP). AEP is a wire format with two sides: a runner that drives an agent and emits events, and a supervisor that declares the environment via a Config (tools, verifiers, re_observation, boundary, on_failure).

Trigger for: writing or wrapping a runner over any LLM/SDK (Anthropic, OpenAI, Claude Agent SDK, LangChain, custom); authoring a supervisor Config; questions about AEP events, RPC patterns (tool_exec_request/resolved, re_observation_request/resolved), source tagging, cache-token accounting, boundary semantics, RunStateSnapshot, conformance cases, the v0.1 spec, or imports of `aep`/`aep_anthropic`/`aep_claude_agent`. Trigger for any "my AEP run does X, why?" debugging — even when only AEP primitives appear without naming AEP.

Do NOT trigger for generic agent observability, OpenTelemetry, prompt engineering, LLM cost dashboards, or unrelated multi-agent frameworks where AEP is not the chosen protocol.

